    <!-- ═══ WHAT THE MODEL DOESN'T CAPTURE ═══ -->
    <h2>What This Model Doesn't Capture</h2>
    <p>No model is complete. Here's what a DCF inherently misses — and how it might bias our estimate.</p>

    <h3>Upside risks (our number could be too low)</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>AI Boom:</strong> AI chips require immense complexity and new designs, heavily relying on EDA software. If this supercycle accelerates, Synopsys could see unprecedented growth.</li>
      <li><strong>Margin Re-expansion:</strong> If recent margin compression was strictly tied to temporary investments or integration costs, a snapback to historic FCF margins (30%+) would drastically increase cash flow.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Downside risks (our number could be too high)</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>High Debt Burden:</strong> With over $14B in debt, Synopsys is highly leveraged. Rising interest rates or a prolonged tech slowdown could strain cash flows.</li>
      <li><strong>Geopolitical Tensions:</strong> The semiconductor industry is deeply intertwined with global geopolitics. Export controls or tariffs (especially regarding China) could lock Synopsys out of key markets.</li>
    </ul>

    <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    <div class="faq">
      <details>
        <summary>Why use DCF instead of a P/E or EV/EBITDA multiple?</summary>
        <div class="faq-answer">Multiples tell you what the market <em>is</em> paying — not what a company is <em>worth</em>. A DCF forces you to state explicit assumptions about growth and risk, connecting cash flow generation to actual value.</div>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Why a 9% discount rate?</summary>
        <div class="faq-answer">Synopsys operates in an effective duopoly with extremely high switching costs and mission-critical software. This stability commands a lower required return compared to more volatile tech companies, despite the debt load.</div>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Why is the Net Cash negative?</summary>
        <div class="faq-answer">Synopsys carries significant debt ($14.2B) compared to its cash on hand ($2.8B). In a DCF, we value the enterprise, and must subtract net debt to find the value of the equity (shares).</div>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Is this a buy recommendation?</summary>
        <div class="faq-answer">No. This is an analytical framework for estimating intrinsic value. Whether to buy depends on your personal risk tolerance, portfolio allocation, time horizon, and conviction in the assumptions.</div>
      </details>
    </div>

